# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nhs-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The **2022–2024 National Health Service (NHS) strikes** were a series of concurrent industrial disputes in the publicly funded health services of the United Kingdom.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The disputes related to the several staff groups on the Agenda for Change pay scale, as well as those on the junior doctor and consultant contracts.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Rather than a single confrontation, the industrial disputes took place between workers represented by several unions across various jurisdictions and many NHS trusts.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] This meant that the disputes were each resolved individually over a two year period.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] An early pay rise offer from the Scottish government avoided long-term industrial action in the area.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The bulk of the disputes were resolved by summer 2023, though the junior doctor's strikes continued.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Further strikes in Scotland were averted, and a final resolution for doctors in England took place in September 2024.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The disputes commenced on 6 October 2022, when the Royal College of Nursing (RCN) announced their intention to ballot members for industrial action over a pay rise offer which was less than their requested 5% above inflation.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] This was the first time the union did so in their 106-year history, and was followed by a similar movement from Unison.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] On 10 November, RCN nurses and other medical personnel across the NHS voted to strike.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The nurses stated this was due to failing wages, inflation, overwork, and underfunding caused by the United Kingdom cost-of-living crisis.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Strike dates were announced at midnight on 25 November, with RCN members scheduled to engage in strike action between 08:00 and 20:00 on 15 and 20 December.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The Prime Minister, Rishi Sunak said that the pay offer to nurses was "appropriate and fair".
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] *The Times* reported on 8 December that Sunak was preparing to restrict the rights of NHS workers to strike, including proposals to ban ambulance workers and paramedics from striking.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Jake Berry (the former Chairman of the Conservative Party), Dan Poulter (a former minister in the Department of Health), and Robert Buckland (the former Justice Secretary) called on Sunak to negotiate with unions.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] In Prime Minister's Questions on 14 December, Leader of the Opposition Keir Starmer said that the NHS strikes were "a badge of shame" for the government and that Sunak was in "hibernation" instead of trying to avert the disruption.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Eluned Morgan, the Minister for Health and Social Services in the Welsh government, said she was "saddened" by the NHS strikes but that the Welsh government could not increase their pay offer without "substantial cuts to staffing and essential services" or an increase in investment from Westminster.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] On 14–16 December 2022 a poll for *The Observer* by Opinium found 60% of voters said they supported nurses going on strike, with 29% opposing the strikes.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Strikes were also scheduled on 18 and 19 January 2023.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] On 16 January 2023, the RCN announced a further two strike days for England and Wales on 6 and 7 February, which were described as the biggest so far.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] A pay offer was ultimately made of 4.5% to 6% pay rise depending on grade along with improvements to homeworking allowance, occupational car user allowance and London allowance.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] This was accepted by the union on 26 September 2023.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] On 30 November 2022, the GMB announced that more than 10,000 ambulance workers had voted to strike in nine NHS trusts across England and Wales for the first time since between September 1989 and February 1990.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The affected trusts were the South Western, South East Coast, North West, South Central, North East, East Midlands, West Midlands, Welsh, and Yorkshire ambulance services.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The union called two 24-hour strikes on 21 and 28 December.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] UNISON members at ambulance services in London, Yorkshire, the North West, the North East, and the South West also are to go on strike on 21 December, from noon until midnight.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Unite the Union announced that over 1,600 of its workers in ambulance services in the West Midlands, the North West, and the North East would walk out on 21 December after workers voted by up to 92% for strike action.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Last-minute talks on 20 December between Health Secretary Steve Barclay and union leaders fell through after the government refused to make a new pay offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Will Quince, the Minister of State for Health, advised against "risky activity" or participating in contact sports during the strike.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Stephen Powis, the national medical director of NHS England, asked people to only ring 999 in life-threatening emergencies and to take "sensible steps to keep themselves and others safe", including drinking responsibly and checking up on vulnerable family members and neighbours.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Manchester United decided to reduce capacity at Old Trafford by 12,000 for their Carabao Cup match against Burnley F.C. due to the strike.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The matches between Newcastle United and AFC Bournemouth and between Southampton F.C. and Lincoln City had already been rescheduled to 20 December because of the strikes.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The GMB strikes planned for 28 December were called off on 23 December due to the "amazing public support" and to avoid causing "any additional anxiety" over Christmas.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The strike was rescheduled for 11 January 2023.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] On 18 January 2023, the GMB announced a further four strike days in February, including 6 February, a date that will coincide with one of the nurses strikes, creating the largest strike within the NHS so far.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Ultimately a pay offer was made in England and the union accepted the proposals on April 14, 2023.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] A strike was averted in Scotland after a similar deal on 18 September, 2024.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] During 2022 the British Medical Association (BMA) announced a demand of pay increases to restore junior doctors' pay to match the real term pay levels of 2008.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] According to the union, repeated pay freezes and pay-increases below the inflation level had resulted in real-term pay cuts of nearly 30% for junior doctors since 2008.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The BMA organized a strike ballot, the result of which was announced on 20 February 2023.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] More than 98% of respondents supported strike action, and the BMA subsequently announced a 72-hour strike starting 13 March.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The strike had a significant disruptive impact, causing cancellations of an estimated 175000 appointments and procedures.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Subsequent to the strike, BMA representatives met with Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, Steve Barclay.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The meeting did not result in a resolution of the disputes, and the BMA announced an additional 96-hour strike to take place starting 11 April.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] According to Barclay, the BMA placed a pre-condition on the talks of a 35% pay increase.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] This statement was publicly disputed by the BMA, which accused the government of delaying negotiations and not presenting a credible offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] On 28 June, it was announced that NHS consultants in England would strike over pay conditions on 20 and 21 July.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The BMA stated that junior doctors in England were willing to cancel strikes if the government presented a suitable pay offer, amid demands for wage increases that match inflation.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] A pay offer was made in January 2024, however the BMA voted against it.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] On 5 April 2024, it was announced that the BMA consultants in England had voted to accept a revised offer to end strikes after the previous vote to reject.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] One aspect of the new agreement was some reform of the DDRB, including using international comparators to help make pay recommendations.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Following the 2024 general election, new negotiations were held with the incoming Labour government, which ended the dispute with Junior doctors on 17 September.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] As health is a devolved matter, the Scottish government was able to act independently in this regard, and made an offer in December 2022.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] This was accepted by a number of the unions, and avoided industrial action in the country.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Humza Yousaf, the Cabinet Secretary for Health and Social Care, said that the proposal was the "best and final pay offer" available and that there was "nothing left in the coffers" to improve it further.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The RCN, Royal College of Midwives (RCM), the Chartered Society of Physiotherapy (CSP), Unite, Unison and the GMB launched consultative members ballots on the offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Unite members accepted the pay deal, with 64% voting in favour.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Sharon Graham, Unite general secretary, said that the improved pay result was "a testament to the resolve of our members".
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Unison members voted by 57% to accept the offer on a turnout of 63%.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Yousaf said that he was "delighted" that Unite and Unison members had accepted the offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The CSP also voted to accept the deal, with 72% of members in favour.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The RCN did not give a recommendation on whether members should accept or reject the offer, but said that it was still "below our expectations".
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] 82% of RCN members who voted rejected the pay offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Two thirds of GMB members voted to reject the offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The RCM announced on 21 December that 65% of its members had voted against the pay offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Jaki Lambert, the RCM director for Scotland, said following the vote that the offer was "simply not good enough" and that members were "prepared to take industrial action" to get a better deal.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Consequently, the RCN, the RCM and the GMB union rejected the pay offer and Unite and Unison accepted it.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] The Scottish government decided to go ahead with its existing pay offer after Yousaf met with union leaders on 23 December.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] Yousaf said that he would "do everything [he could]" to avert strikes but that there was no more money to increase the offer.
[src:nhs-scotland/2022-present-national-health-service-strikes] *The Scotsman* reported on 27 December that a Savanta poll it had commissioned between 16 and 21 December showed that 66% of respondents would support nurses striking, compared to 23% in opposition.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:nhs-scotland/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
[src:nhs-scotland/academy-of-medical-royal-colleges-and-faculties-in-scotland] The **Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland** is commonly known as the "Scottish Academy", but is not to be confused with the Royal Scottish Academy, which promotes contemporary Scottish art.
[src:nhs-scotland/academy-of-medical-royal-colleges-and-faculties-in-scotland] It is analogous to the Academy of Medical Royal Colleges but is an independent organisation.
[src:nhs-scotland/academy-of-medical-royal-colleges-and-faculties-in-scotland] Trainee doctor representatives from the member organisations form the Scottish Academy Trainee Doctors' Group (SATDG).
[src:nhs-scotland/academy-of-medical-royal-colleges-and-faculties-in-scotland] This provides trainee input into the work of the Scottish Academy and also acts as an independent, coordinated trainee voice in Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/academy-of-medical-royal-colleges-and-faculties-in-scotland] The Academy produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:nhs-scotland/academy-of-medical-royal-colleges-and-faculties-in-scotland] The investigation was launched after recent scandals in the health service and found the problems had been predominantly caused by the failure of clinical staff and NHS management to work together.
[src:nhs-scotland/academy-of-medical-royal-colleges-and-faculties-in-scotland] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking but bullying was endemic Their 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol relieves pain in both acute mild migraine and episodic tension headache.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The aspirin/paracetamol/caffeine combination also helps with both conditions when the pain is mild and is recommended as a first-line treatment for them.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] At a standard dose, paracetamol slightly reduces fever, though it is inferior to ibuprofen in that respect and the benefits of its use for fever are unclear, particularly in the context of fever of viral origins.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is effective for pain after wisdom tooth extraction, but it is less effective than ibuprofen.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The combination of paracetamol and ibuprofen provides greater analgesic efficacy than either drug alone.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The pain relief paracetamol provides in osteoarthritis is small and clinically insignificant.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Evidence supporting its use in low back pain, cancer pain, and neuropathic pain is insufficient.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is the first-line treatment for pain and fever in pregnancy; no causal association with neurodevelopmental disorders has been established, while untreated pain and fever can harm the mother and fetus.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] When used as directed, at a recommended maximum daily dose for an adult of three to four grams, paracetamol is safe and effective in the short term, with uncommon adverse effects similar to those of ibuprofen.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It is often used in patients who cannot tolerate nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) like ibuprofen, than which paracetamol is typically safer in long-term use.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] However, chronic consumption of paracetamol may result in a drop in hemoglobin level, indicating possible gastrointestinal bleeding, and abnormal liver function tests, and higher doses may lead to toxicity, including liver failure.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol poisoning is the foremost cause of acute liver failure in the Western world, and accounts for most drug overdoses in the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol was first made in 1878 by Harmon Northrop Morse or possibly in 1852 by Charles Frédéric Gerhardt.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It is the most commonly used medication for pain and fever in both the United States and Europe.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is available as a generic medication, with brand names including Tylenol and Panadol, among others.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 2023, it was the 112th most commonly prescribed medication in the United States, with more than 5 million prescriptions.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] However, there has been a lack of research on its antipyretic properties, particularly in adults, and thus its benefits are unclear.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] As a result, it has been described as over-prescribed for this application.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In addition, low-quality clinical data indicates that when used for the common cold, paracetamol may relieve a stuffed or runny nose, but not other cold symptoms such as sore throat, malaise, sneezing, or cough.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] For people in critical care, paracetamol decreases body temperature by only 0.2–0.3 °C more than control interventions and does not affect their mortality.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It did not change the outcome in febrile patients with stroke.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The results are contradictory for paracetamol use in sepsis: higher mortality, lower mortality, and no change in mortality were all reported.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol offered no benefit in the treatment of dengue fever and was accompanied by a higher rate of liver enzyme elevation: a sign of potential liver damage.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Overall, there is no support for a routine administration of antipyretic drugs, including paracetamol, to hospitalized patients with fever and infection.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The efficacy of paracetamol in children with fever is unclear.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol should not be used solely to reduce body temperature; however, it may be considered for children with fever who appear distressed.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It appears that 0.2 °C decrease of the body temperature in children after a standard dose of paracetamol is of questionable value, particularly in emergencies.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Based on this, some physicians advocate using higher doses that may decrease the temperature by as much as 0.7 °C.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Meta-analyses showed that paracetamol is less effective than ibuprofen in children (marginally less effective, according to another analysis), including children younger than 2 years old, with equivalent safety.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Exacerbation of asthma occurs with similar frequency for both medications.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is used for the relief of mild to moderate pain such as headache, muscle aches, minor arthritis pain, and toothache, as well as pain caused by cold, flu, sprains, and dysmenorrhea.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It is recommended, in particular, for acute mild to moderate pain, since the evidence for the treatment of chronic pain is insufficient.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The benefits of paracetamol in musculoskeletal conditions, such as osteoarthritis and backache, are uncertain.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It appears to provide only small and not clinically important benefits in osteoarthritis.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] American College of Rheumatology and Arthritis Foundation guideline for the management of osteoarthritis notes that the effect size in clinical trials of paracetamol has been very small, which suggests that for most individuals it is ineffective.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The guideline conditionally recommends paracetamol for short-term and episodic use to those who do not tolerate nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] For people taking it regularly, monitoring for liver toxicity is required.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Essentially the same recommendation was issued by European League Against Rheumatism (EULAR) for hand osteoarthritis.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Similarly, the ESCEO algorithm for the treatment of knee osteoarthritis recommends limiting the use of paracetamol to short-term rescue analgesia only.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is ineffective for acute low back pain.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] No randomized clinical trials evaluated its use for chronic or radicular back pain, and the evidence in favor of paracetamol is lacking.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is effective for acute migraine: 39% of people experience pain relief at one hour compared with 20% in the control group.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The aspirin/paracetamol/caffeine combination also "has strong evidence of effectiveness and can be used as a first-line treatment for migraine".
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol on its own only slightly alleviates episodic tension headache in those who have them frequently.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The German, Austrian, and Swiss headache societies and the German Society of Neurology recommend this combination as a "highlighted" one for self-medication of tension headache, with paracetamol/caffeine combination being a "remedy of first choice", and paracetamol a "remedy of second choice".
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Pain after a dental surgery provides a reliable model for the action of analgesics on other kinds of acute pain.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] For the relief of such pain, paracetamol is inferior to ibuprofen.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Full therapeutic doses of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) ibuprofen, naproxen, or diclofenac are clearly more efficacious than the paracetamol/codeine combination which is frequently prescribed for dental pain.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The combinations of paracetamol and NSAIDs ibuprofen or diclofenac are promising, possibly offering better pain control than either paracetamol or the NSAID alone.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Additionally, the paracetamol/ibuprofen combination may be superior to paracetamol/codeine and ibuprofen/codeine combinations.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] A meta-analysis of general post-surgical pain, which included dental and other surgery, showed the paracetamol/codeine combination to be more effective than paracetamol alone: it provided significant pain relief to as much as 53% of the participants, while the placebo helped only 7%.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol fails to relieve procedural pain in newborn babies.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] For perineal pain postpartum paracetamol appears to be less effective than nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The studies to support or refute the use of paracetamol for cancer pain and neuropathic pain are lacking.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] There is limited evidence in favor of the use of the intravenous form of paracetamol for acute pain control in the emergency department.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The combination of paracetamol with caffeine is superior to paracetamol alone for the treatment of acute pain.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol helps ductal closure in patent ductus arteriosus.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It is as effective for this purpose as ibuprofen or indomethacin, but results in less frequent gastrointestinal bleeding than ibuprofen.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Its use for extremely low birth weight and gestational age infants, however, requires further study.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol has long been established as a safe medication to treat short-term fever and significant pain in pregnant patients.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Regulatory agencies, including the European Medicines Agency (EMA), the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA), the World Health Organization (WHO), and the U.S.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) recommend paracetamol as a first-line analgesic and antipyretic in pregnancy, with use limited to situations where necessary, at the lowest effective dose, and for the shortest duration.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Some observational studies have suggested a possible association between prenatal paracetamol use and neurodevelopmental disorders, including ADHD and autism.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] However, these studies are limited by confounding factors such as maternal fever and infection, and do not demonstrate causation.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Large, well-controlled studies, including sibling-controlled analyses, find no causal link after adjusting for maternal conditions.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Untreated pain and fever can harm mother and fetus.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is excreted in breast milk at measurable concentrations (milk/plasma ratio approximately 1), but the amount ingested by the infant is much lower than paediatric therapeutic doses and rarely associated with clinical effects.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Use during breastfeeding is considered compatible at recommended doses, with extra caution for preterm infants or infants with liver disease.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Gastrointestinal adverse effects such as nausea and abdominal pain are extremely uncommon, and their frequency is substantially lower than with ibuprofen use.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Increase in risk-taking behavior is possible.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Food and Drug Administration (FDA), the drug may cause rare and possibly fatal skin reactions such as Stevens–Johnson syndrome and toxic epidermal necrolysis, Rechallenge tests and an analysis of American but not French pharmacovigilance databases indicated a risk of these reactions.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In clinical trials for osteoarthritis, the number of participants reporting adverse effects was similar for those on paracetamol and on placebo.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] However, the abnormal liver function tests (meaning there was some inflammation or damage to the liver) were almost four times more likely in those on paracetamol, although the clinical importance of this effect is uncertain.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] After 13 weeks of paracetamol therapy for knee pain, a drop in hemoglobin level indicating gastrointestinal bleeding was observed in 20% of participants, this rate being similar to the ibuprofen group.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Due to the absence of controlled studies, most of the information about the long-term safety of paracetamol comes from observational studies.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] These indicate a consistent pattern of increased mortality as well as cardiovascular (stroke, myocardial infarction), gastrointestinal (ulcers, bleeding) and renal adverse effects with increased dose of paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Use of paracetamol is associated with 1.9 times higher risk of peptic ulcer.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Those who take it regularly at a higher dose (more than 2–3 g daily) are at much higher risk (3.6–3.7 times) of gastrointestinal bleeding and other bleeding events.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Meta-analyses suggest that paracetamol may increase the risk of kidney impairment by 23% and kidney cancer by 28%.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol slightly but significantly increases blood pressure and heart rate.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] A review of available research has suggested that an increase in systolic blood pressure and increased risk of gastrointestinal bleeding associated with chronic paracetamol use shows a degree of dose dependence.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The association between paracetamol use and asthma in children has been a matter of controversy.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] However, the most recent research suggests that there is no association, and that the frequency of asthma exacerbations in children after paracetamol is the same as after another frequently used pain killer, ibuprofen.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In recommended doses, the side effects of paracetamol are mild to non-existent.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In contrast to aspirin, it is not a blood thinner (and thus may be used in patients where bleeding is a concern), and it does not cause gastric irritation.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Compared to Ibuprofen—which can have adverse effects that include diarrhea, vomiting, and abdominal pain—paracetamol is well tolerated with fewer side effects.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Prolonged daily use may cause kidney or liver damage.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is metabolized by the liver and is hepatotoxic; side effects may be more likely in chronic alcoholics or patients with liver damage.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Overdose of paracetamol is caused by taking more than the recommended maximum daily dose of paracetamol for healthy adults (three or four grams), and can cause potentially fatal liver damage.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] A single dose should not exceed 1000 mg, doses should be taken no sooner than four hours apart, and no more than four doses (4000 mg) in 24 hours.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] While a majority of adult overdoses are linked to suicide attempts, many cases are accidental, often due to the use of more than one paracetamol-containing product over an extended period.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is hepatotoxic and depletes the stock of the antioxidant glutathione in the liver as glutathione is consumed much faster than it can be replenished.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol toxicity had become the foremost cause of acute liver failure in the United States by 2003, and as of 2005, paracetamol accounted for most drug overdoses in the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] As of 2004, paracetamol overdose resulted in more calls to poison control centers in the U.S. than overdose of any other pharmacological substance.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] According to the FDA, in the United States, "56,000 emergency room visits, 26,000 hospitalizations, and 458 deaths per year [were] related to acetaminophen-associated overdoses during the 1990s.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Overdoses are frequently related to high-dose recreational use of prescription opioids, as these opioids are most often combined with paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The overdose risk may be heightened by frequent consumption of alcohol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Untreated paracetamol overdose results in a lengthy, painful illness.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Signs and symptoms of paracetamol toxicity may initially be absent or non-specific symptoms.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The first symptoms of overdose usually begin several hours after ingestion, with nausea, vomiting, sweating, and pain as acute liver failure starts.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] People who take overdoses of paracetamol do not fall asleep or lose consciousness, although most people who attempt suicide with paracetamol wrongly believe that they will be rendered unconscious by the drug.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Treatment is aimed at removing the paracetamol from the body and replenishing glutathione.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Activated charcoal can be used to decrease absorption of paracetamol if the person comes to the hospital soon after the overdose.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] While the antidote, acetylcysteine (also called *N*-acetylcysteine or NAC), acts as a precursor for glutathione, helping the body regenerate enough to prevent or at least decrease the possible damage to the liver, a liver transplant is often required if damage to the liver becomes severe.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] NAC is usually given following a treatment nomogram for patients with an acute overdose at a known time of ingestion.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Patients with unknown time of ingestion, unreliable history, or repeat supratherapeutic ingestion are treated based on risk assessment.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Toxicity of paracetamol is due to its quinone metabolite NAPQI and NAC also helps in neutralizing it.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Kidney failure is also a possible side effect.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Prokinetic agents such as metoclopramide accelerate gastric emptying, shorten time (tmax) to paracetamol peak blood plasma concentration (Cmax), and increase Cmax.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Medications slowing gastric emptying such as propantheline and morphine lengthen tmax and decrease Cmax.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The interaction with morphine may result in patients failing to achieve the therapeutic concentration of paracetamol; the clinical significance of interactions with metoclopramide and propantheline is unclear.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] There have been suspicions that cytochrome inducers may enhance the toxic pathway of paracetamol metabolism to NAPQI (see Paracetamol#Pharmacokinetics).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] By and large, these suspicions have not been confirmed.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Out of the inducers studied, the evidence of potentially increased liver toxicity in paracetamol overdose exists for phenobarbital, primidone, isoniazid, and possibly St John's wort.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] On the other hand, the anti-tuberculosis drug isoniazid cuts the formation of NAPQI by 70%.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Ranitidine increased paracetamol area under the curve (AUC) 1.6-fold.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] AUC increases are also observed with nizatidine and cisapride.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The effect is explained by these drugs inhibiting glucuronidation of paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol raises plasma concentrations of ethinylestradiol by 22% by inhibiting its sulfation.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol increases INR during warfarin therapy and should be limited to no more than 2 g per week.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol appears to exert its effects through two mechanisms: the inhibition of cyclooxygenase (COX) and actions of its metabolite *N*-arachidonoylphenolamine (AM404).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] This occurs only when the concentration of arachidonic acid and peroxides is low; under these conditions, COX-2 is the predominant form of cyclooxygenase, which explains the apparent COX-2 selectivity of paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The second mechanism centers on the paracetamol metabolite AM404.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] This metabolite has been detected in the brains of animals and cerebrospinal fluid of humans taking paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It is formed in the brain from another paracetamol metabolite 4-aminophenol by action of fatty acid amide hydrolase.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] AM404 is a weak agonist of cannabinoid receptors CB1 and CB2, an inhibitor of endocannabinoid transporter, and a potent activator of TRPV1 receptor.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] This and other research indicate that the endocannabinoid system and TRPV1 may play an important role in the analgesic effect of paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 2018, Suemaru *et al*. found that, in mice, paracetamol exerts an anticonvulsant effect by activation of the TRPV1 receptors and a decrease in neuronal excitability by hyperpolarization of neurons.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The exact mechanism of the anticonvulsant effect of paracetamol is not clear.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] According to Suemaru *et al*., acetaminophen and its active metabolite AM404 show a dose-dependent anticonvulsant activity against pentylenetetrazol-induced seizures in mice.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 2025, Maatuf *et al.* reported that AM404 is also produced by peripheral sensory neurons *in vitro* and blocks the action of pain-sensing Nav1.8 and 1.7 channels at nanomolar concentrations.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] AM404 injected into the hind paw of rats increases the pain threshold for the treated paw, but not the untreated paw, confirming the peripheral nature of this effect.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] It also lowers pain responses in a few other *in vivo* models when injected directly into the affected area.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Other tested metabolites of paracetamol do not block pain-sensing sodium channels *in vitro*.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] After being taken by mouth, paracetamol is rapidly absorbed from the small intestine, while absorption from the stomach is negligible.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Thus, the rate of absorption depends on stomach emptying.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Food slows the stomach's emptying and absorption, but the total amount absorbed stays the same.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In the same subjects, the time to reach peak plasma concentration of paracetamol was 20 minutes in a fasting state, compared to 90 minutes in a fed state.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Furthermore, a high-carbohydrate meal reduced the peak plasma concentration by approximately fourfold, an effect not observed with high-protein or high-fat meals.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol's bioavailability is dose-dependent: it increases from 63% for 500 mg dose to 89% for 1000 mg dose.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Its plasma terminal elimination half-life is 1.9–2.5 hours, and volume of distribution is roughly 50 L.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Protein binding is negligible, except under the conditions of overdose, when it may reach 15–21%.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The concentration in serum after a typical dose of paracetamol usually peaks below 30 μg/mL (200 μmol/L).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] After 4 hours, the concentration is usually less than 10 μg/mL (66 μmol/L).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is metabolized primarily in the liver, mainly by glucuronidation and sulfation, and the products are then eliminated in the urine (see the Scheme on the right).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Only 2–5% of the drug is excreted unchanged in the urine.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Glucuronidation by UGT1A1 and UGT1A6 accounts for 50–70% of the drug metabolism.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Additional 25–35% of paracetamol is converted to sulfate by sulfation enzymes SULT1A1, SULT1A3, and SULT1E1.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] A minor metabolic pathway (5–15%) of oxidation by cytochrome P450 enzymes, mainly by CYP2E1, forms a toxic metabolite known as NAPQI (*N*-acetyl-*p*-benzoquinone imine).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] NAPQI is responsible for the liver toxicity of paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] At usual doses of paracetamol, NAPQI is quickly detoxified by conjugation with glutathione.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The non-toxic conjugate APAP-GSH is taken up in the bile and further degraded to mercapturic and cysteine conjugates that are excreted in the urine.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In overdose, glutathione is depleted by a large amount of formed NAPQI, and NAPQI binds to mitochondria proteins of the liver cells, causing oxidative stress and toxicity.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Yet another minor but important direction of metabolism is deacetylation of 1–2% of paracetamol to form *p*-aminophenol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] *p*-Aminophenol is then converted in the brain by fatty acid amide hydrolase into AM404, a compound that may be partially responsible for the analgesic action of paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The classical methods for the production of paracetamol involve the acetylation of 4-aminophenol with acetic anhydride as the last step.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] They differ in how 4-aminophenol is prepared.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In one method, nitration of phenol with nitric acid affords 4-nitrophenol, which is reduced to 4-aminophenol by hydrogenation over Raney nickel.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In another method, nitrobenzene is reduced electrolytically giving 4-aminophenol directly.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Additionally, 4-nitrophenol can be selectively reduced by Tin(II) Chloride in absolute ethanol or ethyl acetate to produce a 91% yield of 4-aminophenol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Acetanilide was the first aniline derivative serendipitously found to possess analgesic as well as antipyretic properties, and was quickly introduced into medical practice under the name of Antifebrin by Cahn & Hepp in 1886.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Some reports state that Cahn & Hepp or a French chemist called Charles Gerhardt first synthesized paracetamol in 1852.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Harmon Northrop Morse synthesized paracetamol at Johns Hopkins University via the reduction of *p*-nitrophenol with tin in glacial acetic acid in 1877, but it was not until 1887 that clinical pharmacologist Joseph von Mering tried paracetamol on humans.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 1893, von Mering published a paper reporting on the clinical results of paracetamol with phenacetin, another aniline derivative.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Von Mering claimed that, unlike phenacetin, paracetamol had a slight tendency to produce methemoglobinemia.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol was then quickly discarded in favor of phenacetin.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The sales of phenacetin established Bayer as a leading pharmaceutical company.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Von Mering's claims remained essentially unchallenged for half a century until two teams of researchers from the United States analysed the metabolism of acetanilide and phenacetin.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 1947, David Lester and Leon Greenberg found strong evidence that paracetamol was a major metabolite of acetanilide in human blood, and in a subsequent study, they reported that large doses of paracetamol given to albino rats did not cause methemoglobinemia.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 1948, Bernard Brodie, Julius Axelrod and Frederick Flinn confirmed that paracetamol was the major metabolite of acetanilide in humans, and established that it was just as efficacious an analgesic as its precursor.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] They also suggested that methemoglobinemia is produced in humans mainly by another metabolite, phenylhydroxylamine.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] A follow-up paper by Brodie and Axelrod in 1949 established that phenacetin was also metabolized to paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] This led to a "rediscovery" of paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol was first marketed in the United States in 1950 under the name Trigesic, a combination of paracetamol, aspirin, and caffeine.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Reports in 1951 of three users stricken with the blood disease agranulocytosis led to its removal from the marketplace, and it took several years until it became clear that the disease was unconnected.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The following year, 1952, paracetamol returned to the U.S. market as a prescription drug.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In the United Kingdom, marketing of paracetamol began in 1956 by Sterling-Winthrop Co. as Panadol, available only by prescription, and promoted as preferable to aspirin since it was safe for children and people with ulcers.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 1963, paracetamol was added to the *British Pharmacopoeia*, and has gained popularity since then as an analgesic agent with few side-effects and little interaction with other pharmaceutical agents.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Concerns about paracetamol's safety delayed its widespread acceptance until the 1970s, but in the 1980s, paracetamol sales exceeded those of aspirin in many countries, including the United Kingdom.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] This was accompanied by the commercial demise of phenacetin, blamed as the cause of analgesic nephropathy and hematological toxicity.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Available in the U.S. without a prescription since 1955 (1960, according to another source), paracetamol has become a common household drug.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In 1988, Sterling Winthrop was acquired by Eastman Kodak which sold the over the counter drug rights to SmithKline Beecham in 1994.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In June 2009, an FDA advisory committee recommended that new restrictions be placed on paracetamol use in the United States to help protect people from the potential toxic effects.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The maximum single adult dosage would be decreased from 1000 mg to 650 mg, while combinations of paracetamol and other products would be prohibited.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Committee members were particularly concerned by the fact that the then-present maximum dosages of paracetamol had been shown to produce alterations in liver function.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Manufacturers had three years to limit the amount of paracetamol in their prescription drug products to 325 mg per dosage unit.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In November 2011, the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency revised UK dosing of liquid paracetamol for children.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In September 2013, "Use Only as Directed", an episode of the radio program *This American Life* highlighted deaths from paracetamol overdose.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] This report was followed by two reports by ProPublica alleging that the "FDA has long been aware of studies showing the risks of acetaminophen.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In September 2025, US President Donald Trump and HHS Secretary Robert F.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Kennedy Jr. claimed that Tylenol may cause autism and urged pregnant women to avoid it; medical experts, major health organizations, and international studies strongly dispute any causal link, emphasizing that the drug remains safe for treating pain and fever in pregnancy.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is the Australian Approved Name and the British Approved Name as well as the international nonproprietary name that is used by the World Health Organization (WHO); acetaminophen is the United States Adopted Name and the Japanese Accepted Name.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Both paracetamol and acetaminophen are contractions of chemical names for the compound.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The word paracetamol is a shortened form of para-acetylaminophenol, and was coined by Frederick Stearns & Co in 1956, while the word acetaminophen is a shortened form of N-acetyl-p-aminophenol (APAP), which was coined and first marketed by McNeil Laboratories in 1955.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The initialism APAP is used by dispensing pharmacists in the United States.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is available in oral, suppository, and intravenous forms.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Intravenous paracetamol is sold under the brand name Ofirmev in the United States.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In some formulations, paracetamol is combined with the opiate codeine, sometimes referred to as co-codamol (BAN) and Panadeine in Australia.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] In the U.S., this combination is available only by prescription.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] As of 1 February 2018, medications containing codeine also became prescription-only in Australia.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is also combined with other opioids such as dihydrocodeine, referred to as co-dydramol (British Approved Name (BAN)), oxycodone or hydrocodone.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Another very commonly used analgesic combination includes paracetamol in combination with propoxyphene napsylate.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] A combination of paracetamol, codeine, and the doxylamine succinate is also available.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is also available combined with butalbital and caffeine as a treatment for tension and migraine headaches.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is sometimes combined with phenylephrine hydrochloride.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Sometimes a third active ingredient, such as ascorbic acid, caffeine, chlorpheniramine maleate, or guaifenesin is added to this combination.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is extremely toxic to cats, which lack the necessary UGT1A6 enzyme to detoxify it.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Initial symptoms include vomiting, salivation, and discoloration of the tongue and gums.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Unlike an overdose in humans, liver damage is rarely the cause of death; instead, methemoglobin formation and the production of Heinz bodies in red blood cells inhibit oxygen transport by the blood, causing asphyxiation (methaemoglobinaemia and haemolytic anaemia).
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Acetylcysteine is used to treat cats with toxicity arising from paracetamol.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol has been reported to be as effective as aspirin in the treatment of musculoskeletal pain in dogs.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is considered a weak analgesic and is usually combined with codeine, although the efficacy of this formulation has not been evaluated.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] The main effect of toxicity in dogs is liver damage, and GI ulceration has been reported.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Acetylcysteine treatment is efficacious in dogs when administered within two hours of paracetamol ingestion.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Paracetamol is lethal to snakes and has been suggested as a chemical control program for the invasive brown tree snake (*Boiga irregularis*) in Guam.
[src:nhs-scotland/acetaminophen] Doses of 80 mg are inserted into dead mice that are scattered by helicopter as lethal bait to be consumed by the snakes.
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] Aberdeen, Glasgow and Southampton airports were originally owned and operated by the British Airports Authority, which acquired them in the 1970s.
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] In the late 1980s the authority was sold off by the government and became BAA plc.
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] By 2012 BAA had sold off three of its seven airports and rebranded as Heathrow Airport Holdings (HAH).
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] In 2014 HAH decided to sell off Aberdeen, Glasgow and Southampton to enable the company to focus on improving Heathrow for passengers and winning support for Heathrow expansion.
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] Meanwhile, AGS Airports was formed by Ferrovial and Macquarie Group.
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] In December 2014, three months after being incorporated, AGS acquired Aberdeen, Glasgow and Southampton Airports from HAH.
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] In November 2024, it was announced that terms had been agreed to sell AGS for £1.53 billion to AviAlliance.
[src:nhs-scotland/ags-airports] In March 2025 Blackstone acquired a 22% shareholding in AGS with AviAlliance retaining the other 78%.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] At the founding of the National Health Service in the United Kingdom, three separate institutions were created in Scotland, England and Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The NHS in Scotland was accountable to the Secretary of State for Scotland rather than the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care as in England and Wales.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Prior to 1948, a publicly funded healthcare system, the Highlands and Islands Medical Service, had been established in Scotland in 1913.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Following Scottish devolution in 1999, health and social care policy and funding became devolved to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] It is currently administered through the Health and Social Care Directorates of the Scottish Government.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The current Cabinet Secretary for Health and Social Care is Neil Gray, and the head of staff is the director-general health and social care and chief executive of NHS Scotland, Caroline Lamb.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Prior to the creation of NHS in Scotland in 1948, the state was involved with the provision of healthcare, though it was not universal.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Fourpence per week was beyond the means of most crofters at the time, who were subsistence farmers but often provided many troops for British armed forces.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Average crofting families' income in some areas could be as low as £26 per annum (10/- or 120d per week) or even lower.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The additional challenges of delivering medical care in the sparsely populated highlands and islands with poor infrastructure were also funded by the Highlands and Islands Medical Service.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] During the Second World War, the Emergency Hospital Service (Scotland) built many hospitals intended to treat wartime casualties and injuries.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] These hospitals initially lay idle and so the Scottish Secretary at the time decided to use the hospital capacity to reduce long waiting lists for treatment.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Scotland also had its own distinctive medical tradition, centred on its medical schools rather than private practice, and a detailed plan for the future of health provision based on the Cathcart report.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Following the publication of the Beveridge Report in 1942, the UK Government responded with a white paper, *A National Health Service* (Cmd.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] 6502) in 1944 led by the Conservative MP and Minister for Health Henry Willink.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] "The decision to establish the new service applies, of course, to Scotland as well as to England and Wales and the present Paper is concerned with both countries.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The differing circumstances of Scotland are bound to involve certain differences of method and of organisation, although not of scope or of object ...
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The UK Parliament passed the National Health Service (Scotland) Act 1947, which came into effect on 5 July 1948.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This foundational legislation has since been superseded.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The NHS in Scotland was created as an administratively separate organisation in 1948 under the ministerial oversight of the Scottish Office, before being politically devolved in 1999.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This separation of powers and financing is not always apparent to the general public due to the co-ordination and co-operation where cross-border emergency care is involved.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This Act provided a uniform national structure for services which had previously been provided by a combination of the Highlands and Islands Medical Service, local government, charities and private organisations which in general was only free for emergency use.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The new system was funded from central taxation and did not generally involve a charge at the time of use for services concerned with existing medical conditions or vaccinations carried out as a matter of general public health requirements; prescription charges were a later introduction in 1951.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Current provision of healthcare is the responsibility of 14 geographically based local NHS boards, six national special health boards, supported by Public Health Scotland, plus many small contractors for primary care services.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Hospitals, district nursing services and healthcare planning are managed by health boards.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Government policy has been to use the National Waiting Times centre to address waiting lists and limit use of the private sector.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] NHS Scotland had an operating budget of £15.3 billion in 2020/21.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The 2025–26 Scottish budget allocated an annual budget of £21 billion to NHS Scotland, an increase of £139 million from the previous years budget.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Approximately 160,000 staff work across 14 regional NHS Boards, six Special NHS Boards and one public health body, More than 12,000 of these healthcare staff are engaged under independent contractor arrangements.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Descriptions of staff numbers can be expressed as headcount and by Whole-Time Equivalent (WTE) which is an estimate that helps to take account of full and part-time work patterns.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] To have access to NHS services, patients should register with a General Practice.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Most often this will be an independent contractor who has agreed to provide general medical services to patients, funded on a capitation basis, with weighting given for the age distribution, poverty, and rurality.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Various services are provided free of charge by General Practitioners (GPs), who are responsible for maintaining a comprehensive medical record, usually affording some continuity of care.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] There is no option to self-refer to specialists in Scotland unlike many European countries.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] GP surgeries consist of partner GPs who are responsible for running the practice, and may include GPs employed by the practice and paid a salary, but who do not have any responsibility in running the surgery.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In some instances, GPs are directly employed by the local health board, such as in parts of the Highlands and Islands.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The NHS in Scotland also covers dentistry for patients who have registered with a dentist who has agreed to provide services to NHS patients.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Most dentists in Scotland have a mixture of NHS patients and private patients.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Check-ups are free, however dentists charge patients a regulated fee.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Patients in Scotland must pay up to 80% of the total cost of the treatment unless they qualify for free treatment or help with costs.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Dentists are remunerated through a voucher towards treatment and patients can choose to have more expensive treatments if they are willing and able to do so.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This is mostly commonly seen with dental amalgam restorations on molars, which are available on the NHS, whereas composite resin restorations are not.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The patient 'opts-out' of the NHS treatment and pays for the composite restoration as temporary private patient, but remains an NHS patient for future checkups.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Community pharmacies in Scotland also provide prescribed medicines free of charge, where the patient is registered with a GP Surgery based in Scotland, and where the appropriate prescription-voucher is given.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Like GPs, they are private providers who deliver NHS services under contract.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Pharmacists are increasingly delivering services which were once the responsibilities of GPs, such as flu vaccinations as well as offering advice on skin problems, gastrointestinal problems and other minor illnesses.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Pharmacies in Scotland are frequently located inside Chemists' shops and supermarkets.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] While there are no prescription charges in Scotland, prescription-vouchers are not ordinarily given in Scotland for certain medicines - such as acetaminophen and ibuprofen - as these are available without a prescription at very low prices in most chemists and supermarkets.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Most optometrists in Scotland also provide NHS services, and provide eye examinations, which includes retinal health checks and other eye screening services in addition to sight tests.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Entitlements are mainly for corrective lenses and a predetermined set of frames - which were once known as 'NHS glasses' which attracted some social stigma until the range of frames was extended.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Hospital services are delivered directly by the National Health Service in Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Since devolution, Scottish healthcare policy has been to move away from market-based solutions and towards direct delivery, rather than using the private or voluntary sectors.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Proposals for the establishment of fifteen NHS boards were announced by the Scottish Executive Health Department in December 2000.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Further details about the role and function of the unified NHS health boards were provided in May 2001.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] From 1 October 2001 each geographical health board area had a single NHS board that was responsible for improving health and health services across their local area, replacing the previous decision-making structures of 43 separate boards and trusts.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In April 2004, Scotland's health care system became an integrated service under the management of NHS boards.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Local authority nominees were added to board membership to improve co-ordination of health and social care.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The remaining 16 Trusts were dissolved from 1 April 2004.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Hospitals are now managed by the acute division of the NHS board.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] By April 2014, there were new joint working arrangements in place between the NHS boards and local authorities came into effect that also included responsibility for social care.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Their new organisations, which took over from CHPs are called Health and Social Care Partnerships (HSCPs).
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2021 a new national Centre for Sustainable Delivery was established to bring together national programmes for scheduled and unscheduled care, waiting times and best practice – and ensure health boards are implementing them.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] There are 14 health boards (HBs) which are the upper tier of the Scottish health care system, reporting directly to the Scottish Government.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] They were created in 1974 as a result of the National Health Service (Scotland) Act 1972 and are based on groups of the local government districts that existed between 1975 and 1996.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] There were initially 15 HBs in 1974 but the Argyll and Clyde HB was abolished and its area absorbed into the Highland and Greater Glasgow HBs on 1 April 2006, with the latter renamed to NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The part of the NHS Argyll and Clyde area which transferred to NHS Highland corresponds to the Argyll and Bute council area.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In January 2008, the Scottish Government announced plans for legislation to bring in direct elections as a way to select people for non-executive positions on health boards.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The Health Committee of the Scottish Parliament had supported plans for directly elected members as a way that might improve public representation.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This plan was abandoned in 2013 after trials in Fife and Dumfries and Galloway resulted in low voter turnout.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] NHS Health Scotland, Health Protection Scotland and Information Services Division were succeeded by Public Health Scotland in April 2020.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This new agency is a collaborative approach by both the Scottish Government and COSLA as a result of the Public Health Reform Programme.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] NHS Education for Scotland and NHS National Services Scotland were succeeded by Public Services Delivery Scotland on 1 April 2026 in an effort to "reduce duplication, scale what works, giving frontline teams more time with patients".
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The NHS in Scotland does have some services provided by the NHS in England – such as NHS Business Services Authority, which processes the payment of dental, optical and pharmacy vouchers and negotiates with pharmaceutical suppliers to negotiate prices per-item down.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The costs for the medicines consumed is borne by the health board that patient's GP surgery is based in.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Some very complex, low volume, highly-specialist hospital services are also provided by NHS trusts in England, such as the Hospital for Tropical Diseases in London.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] These trusts also treat patients from healthcare systems outside the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The Mental Welfare Commission for Scotland is an independent statutory body which protects people with a psychological disorder who are not able to look after their own interests.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] It is funded through the Scottish Government Health & Social Care Directorate, and follows the same financial framework as the NHS in Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The **Scottish Health Council** took over from local Health Councils on 31 March 2005.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Inspection of premises is undertaken by Healthcare Environment Inspectorate and the Care Inspectorate.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] During the COVID-19 pandemic, NHS Scotland established Test and Protect as the national contact tracing service to minimise the spread of the virus within Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The Central Register keeps records of patients resident in Scotland who have been registered with any of the health systems of the United Kingdom.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] It is maintained by the Registrar General.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Its purposes include keeping GPs' patient lists up to date, the control of new NHS numbers issued in Scotland and assisting with medical research.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Scottish patients are identified using a ten-digit number known as the **CHI Number**.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] These are used to uniquely identify individuals, avoiding problems such as where health records of people with similar birth dates and names may be confused, or where ambiguously spelled or abbreviated names may lead to one patient having several different health records.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In addition, CHI numbers are quoted in all clinical correspondence to ensure that there is no uncertainty over the patient in question.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] A similar system of NHS reference numbers has since been instituted by NHS England and Wales.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2000, the NHS boards were starting to help out researchers with their studies.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The Scottish Dental Practice Board, for example, was helping out a study which looked at the significance of orthodontic treatment with fixed appliances.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The SDPB shared 128 subjects with these researchers for analysis.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The SNP led Scottish Government, elected in May 2007, made it clear that it opposed the use of partnerships between the NHS and the private sector.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon voiced opposition to what she termed the "creeping privatisation" of the NHS, and called an end to the use of public money to help the private sector "compete" with the NHS.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Prescription charges were abolished in Scotland in 2011.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The National Health Service and Community Care Act 1990 introduced GP fundholding for certain elective procedures on a voluntary basis.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Fundholding gave GPs significant influence over Trusts' decision making as a significant source of funding.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] GP Fundholding was subsequently abolished with the function transferring to Primary Care Trusts in 1998.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2001, NHS 24, was established to provide advice and triage services for patients outside of the 'core hours' of 08:00–18:30 on any working day.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] They can also advise of pharmacy opening hours.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2002, the Scottish Parliament Acted to introduce free personal care for patients aged over 65 in Community Care and Health (Scotland) Act 2002.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The Scottish Parliament abolished Primary Care Trusts in the National Health Service Reform (Scotland) Act 2004, which abolished the internal market in Scotland and replaced NHS Trusts with 15 territorial health boards.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2004, GPs were no longer required to provide out of hours services unless they opted into doing so.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2005, a plan for improving oral health and modernising dental practices was put into place, known as 'Childsmile', which provides preventive care such as proper brushing technique, tooth varnish and dietary advice.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This has resulted in 60% of children in Scotland having no obvious signs of tooth decay.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] An incentive programme for GPs was established in 2004, known as the Quality and Outcomes Framework (QOF) were introduced in order to reward and incentivize good practice and provided a way for GP surgeries to increase their income.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This was abolished in Scotland in 2015 as QOF compliance was a significant administrative burden for GPs.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The Scottish Government and the British Medical Association agreed the *2018 Scottish General Medical Services Contract* that came in to force 1 April 2018.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2008, the Scottish Government introduced the Scottish Patient Safety Programme, which aimed to reduced iatrogenic illness by changing the safety culture to be more in line with the aviation industry, by providing clinicians with skills in improvement methodology and root cause analysis.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2022 an extra £82.6 million was announced to bolster pharmacy support for repeat prescriptions and medication reviews in GP practices.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The same year, NHS Scotland recruited 191 nurses from overseas.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The nurses were recruited from several countries, including India and Philippines.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] A plan was made to hire another 203 foreign nurses through recruitment agencies.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] A contract was awarded to Inhealthcare for remote monitoring services across Scotland.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] This will enable patients to record relevant information at home and relay the readings to NHS teams for analysis using a mobile app or landline telephone.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] It will be used to manage hypertension, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, asthma, heart disease, diabetes, depression, malnutrition, cancer and COVID.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] There is a substantial effort to develop a drone delivery service.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] It is testing whether drones will improve logistics services, including the transport of laboratory samples, blood products, chemotherapy and medicines.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] It is hoped that this will provide equity of care between urban and remote rural communities.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] At present patients in remote areas may have to travel for hours to reach a hospital able to provide specialised treatment.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Skyports, a drone operator, is running flight trials and live flights should start in 2023.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2014 the Nuffield Trust and the Health Foundation produced a report comparing the performance of the NHS in the four countries of the UK since devolution in 1999.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] They included data for the North East of England as an area more similar to the devolved areas than the rest of England.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] They found that there was little evidence that any one country was moving ahead of the others consistently across the available indicators of performance.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] There had been improvements in all four countries in life expectancy and in rates of mortality amenable to health care.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Despite the hotly contested policy differences between the four countries there was little evidence, where there was comparable data, of any significant differences in outcomes.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The authors also complained about the increasingly limited set of comparable data on the four health systems of the UK.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2014–2015 more than 7,500 NHS patients were treated in private hospitals to meet waiting times targets.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Peter Bennie, of the British Medical Association, attacked the decision to release weekly reports on the Accident and Emergency 4-hour wait target in June 2015.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In June 2015, 92.2% of patients were admitted or discharged within 4 hours against a target of 95%.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The investigation was launched after concerns about high death rates and staffing problems at Monklands Hospital, a *Clostridioides difficile* outbreak at the Vale of Leven Hospital and concerns about patient safety and care at Aberdeen Royal Infirmary.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The report found the problems had been predominantly caused by the failure of clinical staff and NHS management to work together.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking but bullying was endemic.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Their 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In January 2017 the British Medical Association said that the health service in Scotland was "stretched pretty much to breaking point" and needed an increase in funding of at least 4% "just to stand still".
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The service missed seven out of eight performance targets in 2016–2017.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] There was a 99% increase in the number of people waiting more than 12 weeks for an outpatient appointment.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Drug-related deaths were the highest in the European Union.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] NHS Scotland's local health boards also have high vacancy levels in their mental health departments.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2020, it was revealed that over 1 in 8 senior mental health roles were unfilled, which has directly led to increased waiting times for mental health patients.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In November 2022 a survey by Ipsos and the Health Foundation found just 28% of the Scottish public were confident about their devolved government plans for the NHS.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Although patients who live close to the Anglo-Scottish border are able to access services on the other side, cross-border administration is not always streamlined.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] The Coldstream medical practice has about 1400 patients who live in England.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] They benefit from the Scottish free prescriptions because they are "deemed to be in the Scottish healthcare system" so long as they are delivered through a Scottish pharmacy.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] However, there has been no agreement about the reimbursement of hospital charges for patients who cross the border for hospital treatment.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In 2013, 633 Northumberland patients crossed into Scotland for treatment at the Borders General Hospital.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust complained in June 2015 that commissioners outside England use a "burdensome" prior approval process, where a funding agreement is needed before each stage of treatment.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] At the end of 2014–15 the trust was owed more than £2.3m for treating patients from outside England.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] A survey by the Health Service Journal suggested there was £21m of outstanding debt relating to patients from the devolved nations treated in the last three years, against total invoicing of £315m by English NHS trusts.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Funding was approved for 625 referrals outside Scotland in 2016–2017, up from 427 in 2013–2014.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Patients who are not entitled to free NHS treatment because they are not ordinarily resident in the UK are supposed to pay for their treatment.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] Not all of this money is collected. £347,089 was owed to NHS Lothian by 28 patients in 2016–2017, compared with £47,755 owed by fewer than five patients the previous year.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] In Greater Glasgow and Clyde the number of overseas patients treated rose from 67 in 2014–2015 to 99.
[src:nhs-scotland/nhs-scotland] A total of £423,326 is owed to the health board and about £1.2 million across Scotland.
